OK, right. That's because we don't want `orElse` to "recover" from defects. So if there are any defects, we fail it. Well, we can do that in another way:

```scala
       ZIOFn(() => that) { cause =>
         if (cause.died) ZIO.halt(cause)
         else that.catchAllCause(cause2 => ZIO.halt(Cause.die(FiberFailure(cause)) ++ cause2))
       }
```

This is more direct and reflects intention better than `stripFailures`.

Another way would be to cast the Cause, but I guess it's not necessary tbh:

```scala
       ZIOFn(() => that) { cause =>
         if (!cause.failed) ZIO.halt(cause.asInstanceOf[Cause[E2])
         else that.catchAllCause(cause2 => ZIO.halt(Cause.die(FiberFailure(cause)) ++ cause2))
       }
```

